english:
  title: Epitaph for Minister Han Mun-gyeong with Preface
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When I was but sixteen or seventeen, I loved to wander in the company of poet-monks. Once at Myoryeon Temple, I sat among Confucian scholars and Buddhist monks, sipping tea while composing linked verse. Minister Han was then merely twelve or thirteen, yet each couplet he offered struck perfectly true. All present marveled. Even those grown old in letters deferred to him, not daring to claim equal rank. I myself recognized then that he was no ordinary child.

    In the year of Jeong-hai, my father, serving as Director of Examinations, presided over the civil service test. Minister Han indeed passed with highest honors, though he was but fifteen years old. Even those who failed the examination acknowledged his talent, saying, "Han is no fortunate accident." Before this, through hereditary privilege he had twice held minor posts, and so he did not seek advancement. Instead, he devoted himself to ancient texts. Under Master Ikjae, he studied the Spring and Autumn Annals, the Records of the Historians, and the History of Han. In calligraphy, both regular and cursive scripts reached sublime mastery.

    When King Chung-jeong ascended the throne, Han was appointed Registrar of Deok-nyeong Prefecture and placed in the Secretariat, serving as a Secret Advisor. In the year of Sin-myo, when the King withdrew to Ganghwa Island, Han accompanied him. When King Kong-min recalled him to the capital, he was not immediately employed. Not until the year of Gye-sa was he appointed Ceremonial Registrar, again as Secret Advisor. The following year he rose to Assistant Director of Protocols and Royal Drafter. Two years later, he was promoted multiple times: Gentleman of the Court, Lecturer of the National Confucian Academy, Paramount Counselor, and Director of the National Academy, all while serving as Instructor to the Bureau of Civilizations.

    When the official system was reformed in the year of Byeong-shin, he became Gentleman of the Middle Ranks, Vice Director of the Imperial Library, and Royal Drafter. The following year he transferred to the Minister of Military Affairs and became a Hanlin Compiler. That autumn he rose to Censor-in-Chief. The next year he advanced to Grand Counselor, Rector of the National Academy, and Royal Drafter. In the year of Shin-chuk, when the King fled southward to escape bandits, Han was transferred twice, becoming director of both the Ceremonial Bureau and the Examination Bureau, both at the rank of Gentleman. The next autumn, returning to the capital, he was promoted to Grand Counselor, Director of the Bureau of Stables, and Chief Lecturer of the Right Bureau of Culture. Winter brought his appointment as Vice Minister of the Secretariat and Chief Lecturer of the Treasure Repository, with charge of the Bureau of Works—clearly because his wisdom in matters of civil service selection was being recognized. The following year he rose to Right Vice Minister, then to Left Vice Minister.

    In the spring of the year of Ul-sa, Sin Don gained the King's favor through secret means. Minister Han, perceiving this, sent word in confidence: "Sin Don is no righteous man. I fear he will bring chaos. I humbly urge Your Majesty to reflect deeply. Who else would dare speak thus?" Yet the King, besotted with Sin Don, did not heed him. That summer Han was made Minister of Rites, and in autumn appointed to the Military Bureau—clearly a demotion. In the tenth month of that year, his father passed away. After completing three years of mourning, still the King, remembering his candid words, would not employ him.

    When Sin Don's villainy was exposed in the autumn of Sin-hai, the King declared, "Han possessed prescient wisdom. Bring him to me at once." Han was then appointed Grand Counselor, Minister of Personnel, and Scholar of the Hall of Cultivated Literature. After a few days, the King reflected, "The selection of officials is a grave responsibility. Only one with keen intelligence and meticulous precision can wield this authority. I have determined that only Han is equal to this task." Thus he was appointed Right Chancellor with the rank of Gentleman. That winter he was promoted to Left Chancellor with supervision of civil service selection.

    In the summer of the year of Ul-myo, he became Vice Director of the Secretariat and Lecturer on the Royal Classics. That autumn he rose to Censor-General. In the first month of the following year, he was transferred to Vice Administrator, then shortly after promoted to Joint Administrator. In the fifth month he served as joint director of examinations, selecting thirty-three individuals including the now-Minister Jeong Chong. People of that time praised this as truly finding worthy talent. That autumn he rose to Director. In the year of Muo, he was enfeoffed as Lord of Sangdang and elevated to Paramount Counselor, with his official rank changed to Adept and granted the title Tributary Duke with Merit in Loyalty and Transformation.

    In the winter of Ki-mi, through service in carving the Gwangam Stele, he was returned to the Censor position. The following spring he was enfeoffed as Lord of Cheongseong and elevated to Great Paramount Counselor. In the year of Im-sul, he accompanied the King to the Southern Capital. The following autumn he was promoted for merit to Counselor in Earnest, Director of the Bureau of Eminent Virtue, Chief Lecturer of the Right Bureau of Culture, Director of the Spring and Autumn Annals Bureau, and Chief General of the Upper Guard, his title remaining unchanged.

    On the twenty-eighth day of the second month in the year of Gap-ja, he passed away from illness in his residence. The people of the nation all lamented, saying, "This man lived but fifty-two years—how can Heaven's way be so cruel?" He was buried in the southern foothills of the ancestral grave in Seogok Valley, Imjin County, according to proper rite.

    The Han clan of Sangdang is a great house. Nan was a Meritorious Servant of the Three Han Dynasties. Sae-gi served as Right Counselor of the Chancellery, Scholar of the Treasure Repository, and Royal Drafter—he was Han's great-grandfather. Ak rose to be Meritorious Subject for Diligent Service, Three-fold Paramount Counselor of the Three Han Dynasties enfeoffed as Duke of Sangdang, posthumously titled Seo-suk. He served as Prime Minister under King Chung-suk and brought glory to the state—he was Han's grandfather.

    Great-grandfather Seo-suk had five sons, all of whom became illustrious ministers. The one named Kong-ui passed through various posts to become Great Paramount Counselor and Lord of Cheongseong, with the posthumous title Pyeong-gan. He married a daughter of Vice Minister of the Secretariat and Inspector-General Gyeong Sa-man—these were Han's parents. Minister Han married a daughter of Gyeong Jeok, Lord of Gilchang and Keeper of the Gate of the Chancellery, and had four sons and six daughters.

    His eldest son, Sang-hwan, was former Right Counselor of the Three Excellencies. His second son, Sang-jil, was Inspector-General and Governor of Pyongyang. His third son, Sang-gyeong, was Grand Commandant of Works, Royal Drafter, and Vice Minister of Rites. His youngest son, Sang-deok, was Assistant Minister of the Imperial Genealogy Bureau.

    The eldest son, the former Right Counselor, married a daughter of Yin Seung-soon, Gentleman of the Chancellery, and had two daughters, both still young. The Inspector-General married a daughter of Li Seong-rim, Keeper of the Gate of the Chancellery, and had one daughter who married the former Assistant Minister Gang Chaek. He then took a second wife, a daughter of Song Sin-ui, Governor of Cheongpung, and had another daughter still young. The Commandant married a daughter of O Jun-ryang, former Minister of Works, and had one young daughter. The Assistant Minister married a daughter of the former Vice Minister Li Kui-saeng.

    Of his six daughters: the eldest married Right Counselor Ahn Gyeong-geom and bore five daughters and one son. The second married Lecturer of the National Academy Li Jak and bore two sons and one daughter, all still young. The third married Chief General Gwon Bang-wi. The fourth married the former Chief General Im Jung-seon and bore four sons. The fifth married Deputy Director of Euiduk Park Deung, and the sixth married Colonel Jeon Bo.

    His eldest son, though brilliant and fond of learning, abandoned his studies due to illness. His second son passed the examination of Gyeongsin at third place. His third son passed the examination of Imsul at third place. His youngest son passed the examination of Eulchuk at ninth place. By royal custom, when three sons attain the civil service, the mother receives stipends from the state treasury for life. Thus does the Lady Gwon enjoy this honor, and surely the Minister smiles from beneath the earth.

    Nine years have passed since his ascension to the celestial realm, yet his voice and countenance remain ever present before my mind and eyes. How could I ever forget? His second son came with his brothers seeking that these words be inscribed in his tomb. Alas, what sorrow! By Han's request, I once composed an epitaph for his father, Minister Pyeong-gan. Now I compose one for Minister Han himself. How can my heart not ache?

    The epitaph reads:

    Jade vessel holding ice—
    Such was his crystalline purity.
    Mirror unveiled from dust—
    Such was his luminous mind.
    Cradled in silk and comfort,
    yet free from frivolous excess.
    Wandering through poetry and books,
    yet untouched by the smallest greed.
    Filial and fraternal, loyal and true,
    Incorruptible, serene, generous, and kind—
    He should have lived to a ripe age.
    Why did Heaven snatch him away?

    Yet he left many children,
    talented and fair.
    His name lives on in their light,
    as if he still walked this world.
    I have inscribed both father and son,
    and my heart cannot help but grieve.
    May the blessings bestowed be many,
    and may his descendants flourish eternally.
  footnotes:
    - Sin Don (辛旽) was a powerful eunuch and confidant of King Kong-min whose eventual downfall and execution in 1388 vindicated Han Mun-gyeong's prescient warning.
    - The 'Gwangam Stele' refers to an inscription Han helped compose, demonstrating his calligraphic mastery.
    - The epitaph form (铭) was a traditional Chinese literary genre often composed for tomb inscriptions, combining biographical narrative with moral exhortation in verse or parallel prose.
